-- Field Journal pen: Marja Aho (Food & the Cabin Table desk). Summer 2026 batch.
insert into public.blog_posts (
  slug, title, kicker, excerpt, category_slug, tags, hero_image, hero_alt,
  content, author_id, author_snapshot, status, published_at, featured,
  read_time_minutes
) values (
  'strawberry-hour-at-the-rovaniemi-market',
  'Strawberry hour at the Rovaniemi market',
  'Rovaniemi · July · Food',
  'The first Finnish strawberries reach the Rovaniemi market in early July, and for a few weeks the whole town organises itself around a wooden crate. A field report on berries, new potatoes, and fried vendace eaten standing up.',
  'food',
  ARRAY['food','rovaniemi','market','strawberries','summer']::text[],
  '/images/summer-market-strawberries-1200.webp',
  'Wooden crates of ripe red strawberries on a market stall in warm northern evening light',
  '[{"type":"paragraph","text":"There is a particular sound a Finnish market makes in the first week of July, and it is the sound of cardboard trays being slapped down onto a folding table at seven in the morning. The strawberries have arrived. Not strawberries in general — those have been in the supermarkets since April, pale Spanish things with the texture of a damp apple — but the Finnish ones, grown in the long light, picked the previous evening, driven north overnight. The difference is not subtle. The difference is the whole point of July."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"I spent three mornings and one long evening at the Rovaniemi market square by the river, eating my way through the short list of things a northern market does in summer, and taking notes so that you do not have to guess. The market is not large. That is part of its charm. There are perhaps a dozen stalls on a good day: berries, new potatoes, smoked fish, fried fish, peas in the pod, someone selling jam and someone selling knitted socks with a seriousness that suggests they know something about August that the tourists do not."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The berry economics of a small northern town"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The strawberries are sold by the litre and by the box, and the seller will offer you a taste before you commit, holding out the tray with the studied neutrality of a person who knows exactly how this ends. The berry is warm from the morning sun. It is red all the way through — you can check, and I did, because a certain scepticism is healthy at any market. It tastes concentrated, almost cooked, the sugar built up through twenty-hour days. The season is short and everyone behaves accordingly. People do not buy a litre. They buy a litre to eat now, walking, and a box for the freezer, and then they come back two days later and repeat the transaction with the guilty face of a person who told themselves the box would last a week."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"Prices move with the season and I am not going to pretend to quote you one that will still be true when you read this. Early July, first Finnish berries of the year, expect to pay real money and consider it fair. By late July the price relaxes. The flavour, in my experience, does not."},{"type":"pullquote","text":"A supermarket strawberry is a photograph of a strawberry. This is the strawberry."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"New potatoes, dill, and a pot of salted water"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The other pillar of the summer market is the new potato, sold loose from sacks with the soil still on, in sizes from marble to golf ball. The correct preparation is not a recipe, it is a ritual, and every Finn performs it identically: scrub, boil in well-salted water with a fist of dill stalks, drain, butter, more dill, more salt, eat outdoors. Nothing else is added. Anything else would be an admission of doubt, and about this one dish there is no doubt anywhere in the country."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"I bought a kilo of the small ones on the advice of the seller, who told me — with the firmness of a woman who has had this conversation ten thousand times — that the small ones are for butter and the big ones are for salad, and that I did not want the salad. She was right. I cooked them that evening on the cabin stove, and ate them on the porch straight from the pot, and I want to record honestly that I had planned to save half for the next day and did not."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Vendace, eaten standing up"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"At the fried-fish stall the muikku — vendace, a small silver lake fish the length of a finger — go into the pan whole, rolled in rye flour, and come out golden and crackling, served in a paper tray with garlic mayonnaise and a slice of rye bread. You eat them entire, head and all, standing at a chest-high table, and the only utensil involved is your other hand keeping the gulls honest. A tray of them costs about what a coffee and a pastry costs further south, and it is the best fish-to-euro ratio I know of anywhere in this country."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"A colleague of mine on this desk once paid forty-two euros for a bowl of salmon soup in this same town and wrote a whole entry defending the price. I respect the entry and I respect the soup. I would also point out, gently, that four metres from where I stood, the muikku man was operating an entirely different school of economics, and both schools graduate satisfied customers."},{"type":"image","src":"/images/summer-market-strawberries-1200.webp","alt":"Wooden crates of ripe red strawberries on a market stall in warm northern evening light","caption":"First week of July. The trays go down at seven in the morning and the town arranges itself around them.","full":true},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"How to do a Lapland market properly"},{"type":"list","items":["Go in the morning, before ten, when the berries are freshest and the queue is made of locals doing their actual shopping. The tourist hour is later and the good trays are gone by then.","Taste before you buy, and buy from the stall where the seller eats their own stock. This signal has never once failed me.","Ask which potatoes are for butter and which are for salad. Obey the answer.","Eat the fried muikku on site, standing up. They are a different and lesser food ten minutes later.","Bring cash for the smaller stalls. Most take cards now, but the day the card reader sulks is always the day the best berries are on the corner table.","Buy the box for the freezer even though you know how it ends. It ends with an empty box. That is the correct ending."]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The evening market"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"On my last evening I went back at nine, when the stalls were packing up and the light had gone long and warm across the river. The strawberry seller was down to her last four boxes and was no longer offering tastes, because at that hour the berries sell themselves to people walking home. I bought a box I had no plans for. On the bridge I met the reason for the box: I stood there in the low gold light eating strawberries over the railing, one at a time, watching the river push north, and I record for the archive that this is the correct use of a July evening in Rovaniemi and that the box did not survive the bridge."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"Written from a cabin kitchen south of Rovaniemi in the first week of July, next to a pot of new potatoes that was meant to be tomorrow and became tonight."}]'::jsonb,
  NULL,
  '{"handle":"marja","display_name":"Marja Aho","avatar_url":null}'::jsonb,
  'published',
  '2026-07-04'::timestamptz,
  false,
  8
)
